<TITLE> PM orders 'immediate steps' against water logging </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 28 (bdnews24.com)Prime minister Sheikh Hasina on Tuesday asked city agencies to take immediate steps to end water-logging in the capital, as torrential overnight rains in Dhaka broke a half-century record bringing city life to a grinding halt. Hasina summoned the top-brass of the local government ministry, Dhaka City Corporation and WASA to her office, her press secretary said. "She asked the agencies concerned to clean all culverts and drains in the capital," the PM's press secretary Abul Kalam Azad told reporters after the meeting. Azad quoted the prime minister as warning officials that public suffering due to their negligence would not be tolerated. Attending the meeting were the prime minister's adviser HT Imam, state minister for local government Jahangir Kabir Nanak, Dhaka mayor Sadeque Hossain Khoka and Dhaka Metropolitan Police commissioner Shahidul Haque. WASA chairman Golam Mostofa, acting managing director Mahbubur Rahman and the chief engineer of the public works ministry were also present. The meeting followed the prime minister's inauguration of a three-day council of deputy commissioners in Dhaka, that was delayed due to the monsson deluge. The rains and subsequent city floods were discussed in the council. State minister for local government Jahangir Kabir Nanak was also at the WASA Bhaban from 9am to 3pm to resolve water-logging issues in the city after the overnight downpour. bdne
